 Although such examples do not directly falsify Fillmore's ordering hypothesis, taken together with the examples in 3.1,
they do cast doubt on the claim implicit in Fillmore's analysis that there is a strong distinction in kind to be made between the passivizability of the double object con- structions related to to-datives and those related to for- datives.
2.2.4 In fact, the examples cited directly above are re- lated to a larger problem. It is known that there are ex- ceptions to the passive transformation for which there can be no solution based on the ordering of transformations. Jackendoff (1972) has pointed out cases for which Gruber's system of thematic relations provides a promising analysis. For example, in some cases (but not all), the notion of agency is apparently relevant:
